29 Nov 2008
However, Ross, who is reportedly paid £6 million a year, is currently serving a three-month suspension and is due to resume his chat show and Radio 2 programme next year.Mrs Sachs said: "I think Ross should have been sacked - he's a public figure with a level of responsibility and if he can't control his mouth he shouldn't be let loose."Why did the BBC keep him on? I'm sure most people don't want him there, especially on his ridiculously monstrous salary."But Ross does seem very sorry. Although he didn't apologise publicly, he sent flowers and a nice letter."She also disclosed that she had had no idea Miss Baillie, 23, was a burlesque artist in a group called the Satanic Sluts whose act involves simulating a human sacrifice and smearing themselves in blood."There are some things you'd rather not know about your grandchildren," said Mrs Sachs."It all came as a dreadful shock, Some of the images were obviously disturbing and we'd never heard of the Satanic whatevers."But she said that support came from a number of high profile comedians."David Walliams is a friend of Andrew's and we had a lovely card from him saying how the behaviour of Ross and Brand was absolutely out of bounds," said Mrs Sachs, adding that John Cleese, who starred with her husband in Fawlty Towers, had also helped."John couldn't believe it and immediately rang to sympathise," she said. Celebrity news
